<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1436,1787,1919]" pageId="21" pageNumber="280">
Some crucial characters are missing from the original description of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Silvestri" authorityYear="1903" box="[928,1018,1787,1811]" class="Chilopoda" family="Henicopidae" genus="Rhodobius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lithobiomorpha" pageId="21" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lagoi">
<emphasis box="[928,1018,1787,1811]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="280">R. lagoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see Table 1), found on the island of Rhodes, but those described and illustrated suggest a typical Northern Hemisphere anopsobiid with a reduced number of spiracles. Zapparoli &amp; 
<bibRefCitation box="[546,762,1859,1884]" pageId="21" pageNumber="280" refId="ref17423" refString="Zapporoli, M. &amp; Edgecombe, G. D. (2011) Order Lithobiomorpha. In: Minelli, S. (Ed.), Treatise on Zoology, the Myriapoda. Vol. 1. Brill, Leiden, pp. 371 - 389." type="book">Edgecombe (2011)</bibRefCitation>
suggest that it may have been introduced to the island of Rhodes. If so, it would most likely be from some part of Central Asia.
</paragraph>
